data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` (MSTest v3+) to pinpoint exactly which line should throw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor throwing instead of `CreateUser`).
- `ThrowsExactly` scopes the assertion to the specific call.
- You can also inspect the returned exception (e.g., check `ParamName`):

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
    () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```

> **Note:** If you're on MSTest v2, use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` instead — `ThrowsExactly` was added in v3.
